# Cursor AI Rules for Support Ticket Management System

## Project Context
This is a Support Ticket Management System built with Blazor WebAssembly, ASP.NET Core Web API (.NET 9), and SQL Server. The project is part of a .NET AI Capability Exercise focusing on demonstrating effective AI-assisted development across the full software lifecycle.

## Technology Stack Conventions

### .NET 9 and C# 12
- Use modern C# 12 features: file-scoped namespaces, primary constructors where appropriate
- Use top-level statements in Program.cs
- Prefer `var` for local variables when type is obvious
- Use nullable reference types (`#nullable enable`)
- Async/await throughout - all I/O operations must be async
- Use `required` keyword for required properties in DTOs

### ASP.NET Core Web API
- Controllers should inherit from `ControllerBase`
- Use `[ApiController]` attribute on all controllers
- Return `ActionResult<T>` for all action methods
- Use proper HTTP status codes: 200 (OK), 201 (Created), 204 (No Content), 400 (Bad Request), 404 (Not Found), 500 (Internal Server Error)
- Use route templates: `[Route("api/[controller]")]`
- Use HTTP verb attributes: `[HttpGet]`, `[HttpPost]`, `[HttpPut]`, `[HttpDelete]`
- Model binding validation automatically handled by `[ApiController]`

### Entity Framework Core
- DbContext should have scoped lifetime (default)
- Always use async methods: `SaveChangesAsync()`, `ToListAsync()`, `FirstOrDefaultAsync()`
- Configure entities using Fluent API in `OnModelCreating`
- Use migrations for schema changes: `dotnet ef migrations add MigrationName`
- Always include navigation properties for relationships
- Use proper foreign key configurations

### Blazor WebAssembly
- Components should use file-scoped namespace
- Use `@page` directive for routable pages
- Use `[Parameter]` for component parameters
- Use `@inject` for dependency injection
- Handle loading states with boolean flags
- Display user-friendly error messages
- Use `StateHasChanged()` when updating UI after async operations
- Bootstrap 5 for styling

## Naming Conventions

### C# Naming
- **Classes, Methods, Properties:** PascalCase (`TicketService`, `GetTicketById`, `AssignedToId`)
- **Private fields:** _camelCase with underscore (`_dbContext`, `_stateMachine`)
- **Parameters, local variables:** camelCase (`ticketId`, `newStatus`)
- **Interfaces:** IPascalCase (`ITicketStateMachine`, `ITicketService`)
- **Constants:** PascalCase (`MaxTitleLength`)
- **Async methods:** Suffix with `Async` (`CreateTicketAsync`, `SaveChangesAsync`)

### File Naming
- **Controllers:** `[Entity]Controller.cs` (e.g., `TicketsController.cs`)
- **Services:** `[Entity]Service.cs` and `I[Entity]Service.cs`
- **DTOs:** `[Action][Entity]Dto.cs` (e.g., `CreateTicketDto.cs`, `TicketResponseDto.cs`)
- **Entities/Models:** `[Entity].cs` (e.g., `Ticket.cs`, `User.cs`)
- **Blazor Pages:** `[PageName].razor` (e.g., `TicketList.razor`)
- **Components:** `[ComponentName].razor` (e.g., `StatusBadge.razor`)

## Code Organization

### Project Structure
```
src/
  TicketSystem.Api/
    Controllers/
    Services/
    Models/
    DTOs/
    Data/
    Middleware/
    Program.cs
  TicketSystem.Blazor/
    Pages/
    Components/
    Services/
    Program.cs
tests/
  TicketSystem.Tests/
    UnitTests/
    IntegrationTests/
```

### Layer Responsibilities
- **Controllers:** HTTP handling, routing, model binding, delegating to services
- **Services:** Business logic, orchestration, transaction management
- **Data/DbContext:** Database access, entity configurations
- **DTOs:** Data transfer objects for API requests/responses
- **Models/Entities:** Database entities with relationships

## State Machine Requirements

### Critical Piece - Enforce Valid Transitions Only
The ticket state machine is the signature piece of this project. Always validate transitions:

**Valid Transitions:**
- Open â†’ InProgress
- Open â†’ Cancelled
- InProgress â†’ Resolved
- InProgress â†’ Cancelled
- Resolved â†’ Closed

**Invalid Transitions (Must Be Rejected):**
- Open â†’ Resolved
- Open â†’ Closed
- Resolved â†’ InProgress
- Resolved â†’ Open
- Any transition from Closed (terminal state)
- Any transition from Cancelled (terminal state)

**Implementation Pattern:**
```csharp
public interface ITicketStateMachine
{
    bool CanTransition(TicketStatus from, TicketStatus to);
    void ValidateTransition(TicketStatus from, TicketStatus to);
}
```

- `CanTransition` returns true/false
- `ValidateTransition` throws exception if invalid
- Use enums for TicketStatus, not strings in logic
- All status changes must go through state machine validation

## Error Handling

### Backend
- Use global exception handling middleware
- Return structured error responses with consistent format
- Include validation errors in 400 responses
- Log exceptions with sufficient context
- Never expose stack traces to clients in production

### Frontend
- Catch API errors and display user-friendly messages
- Show loading states during async operations
- Handle network failures gracefully
- Validate forms before submission

## Validation Rules

### Required Fields
- Ticket: Title, Description, Priority, CreatedById
- Comment: Message, TicketId, CreatedById

### String Lengths
- Ticket.Title: max 200 characters
- Ticket.Description: max 5000 characters
- Comment.Message: max 2000 characters
- User.Email: max 320 characters

### Enum Validation
- Priority: Low, Medium, High, Critical
- Status: Open, InProgress, Resolved, Closed, Cancelled
- Role: Admin, Agent, User

### Foreign Key Validation
- AssignedToId must exist in Users (if not null)
- CreatedById must exist in Users
- TicketId must exist in Tickets (for comments)

## Testing Standards

### Test Naming
Use format: `MethodName_Scenario_ExpectedResult`
```csharp
[Fact]
public void CreateTicket_ValidData_Returns201Created()

[Fact]
public void ChangeStatus_InvalidTransition_Returns400BadRequest()
```

### State Machine Tests (Mandatory)
- Test all 5 valid transitions succeed
- Test all invalid transitions return 400
- Test state persistence in database
- Use integration tests, not just unit tests

### Test Organization
- UnitTests/ folder for isolated logic tests
- IntegrationTests/ folder for API endpoint tests
- Use WebApplicationFactory for integration tests
- Use SQLite in-memory for test database

## Security Best Practices

### Never Commit
- Passwords or credentials
- API keys or secrets
- Connection strings with passwords

### Always Use
- Parameterized queries (EF Core does this automatically)
- HTTPS in production
- CORS configuration for Blazor
- Input validation on server side
- Environment variables or User Secrets for sensitive data

## Code Quality Standards

### Keep Methods Small
- Max 30-40 lines per method
- Single responsibility principle
- Extract complex logic into separate methods

### Comments
- No obvious comments like "// Create ticket"
- Comment complex business logic
- Comment state machine transition rules
- XML comments on public APIs (optional but recommended)

### DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)
- Extract common logic into services
- Create reusable Blazor components
- Use base classes or extension methods for shared functionality

### Prefer Composition Over Inheritance
- Use dependency injection
- Interface-based design for services
- Avoid deep inheritance hierarchies

## Documentation Standards

### Code Documentation
- XML comments on public methods and classes (optional)
- README with clear setup instructions
- Database setup documented
- API endpoints documented

### AI Usage Documentation
- Track all prompts in ai-prompts/ folder
- Document what was accepted, changed, rejected
- Show iteration and refinement, not copy-paste
- Validate all AI-generated code before committing

## Cursor-Specific Instructions

### When Generating Code
1. Always ask for clarification if requirements are unclear
2. Provide code with proper error handling
3. Include null checks where appropriate
4. Use async/await consistently
5. Follow the naming conventions above
6. Generate code that compiles without modification when possible

### When Refactoring
- Maintain existing patterns in the codebase
- Don't introduce new patterns without explicit request
- Keep changes minimal and focused
- Preserve existing tests

### When Debugging
- Analyze error messages carefully
- Consider state machine rules for status-related errors
- Check database constraints for FK violations
- Verify async/await usage

### When Creating Tests
- Cover happy path and error cases
- Include state machine transition tests
- Use descriptive test names
- Create independent, isolated tests

## Project-Specific Patterns

### Service Layer Pattern
```csharp
public class TicketService : ITicketService
{
    private readonly AppDbContext _context;
    private readonly ITicketStateMachine _stateMachine;

    public TicketService(AppDbContext context, ITicketStateMachine stateMachine)
    {
        _context = context;
        _stateMachine = stateMachine;
    }

    public async Task<TicketResponseDto> CreateTicketAsync(CreateTicketDto dto)
    {
        // Business logic here
    }
}
```

### Controller Pattern
```csharp
[ApiController]
[Route("api/[controller]")]
public class TicketsController : ControllerBase
{
    private readonly ITicketService _ticketService;

    public TicketsController(ITicketService ticketService)
    {
        _ticketService = ticketService;
    }

    [HttpGet("{id}")]
    public async Task<ActionResult<TicketResponseDto>> GetTicket(int id)
    {
        // Delegate to service
    }
}
```

### Blazor Component Pattern
```csharp
@page "/tickets"
@inject ITicketApiService TicketService

<h3>Ticket List</h3>

@if (isLoading)
{
    <p>Loading...</p>
}
else if (errorMessage != null)
{
    <div class="alert alert-danger">@errorMessage</div>
}
else
{
    // Display tickets
}

@code {
    private List<TicketDto> tickets = new();
    private bool isLoading = true;
    private string? errorMessage;

    protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()
    {
        try
        {
            tickets = await TicketService.GetAllTicketsAsync();
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            errorMessage = ex.Message;
        }
        finally
        {
            isLoading = false;
        }
    }
}
```

## Remember
- This is an assessment project demonstrating AI-assisted development
- Documentation is as important as working code
- State machine validation is the critical signature piece
- Always validate AI suggestions before accepting
- Test all generated code
- Maintain prompt history with iterations and decisions
